'''''Memórias Póstumas''''' (known in English as '''''Posthumous Memoirs'''''<ref name=berlin/><ref name=kerala/><ref name=lumiere/> and '''''Posthumous Memories'''''<ref name=nytimes/><ref name=variety/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.barbican.org.uk/music/event-detail.asp?ID=6432 | title=Posthumous Memories (Memórias Póstumas) (12A) + ScreenTalk | publisher=[[Barbican Centre]] | accessdate=April 27, 2014}}</ref>) is a 2001 [[comedy-drama]] film directed by [[André Klotzel]] based on ''[[The Posthumous Memoirs of Bras Cubas]]'' by [[Machado de Assis]]. It follows Brás Cubas, played by [[Reginaldo Faria]] and [[Petrônio Gontijo]], as he recounts his life after his death. 

==Cast==
*[[Reginaldo Faria]] as Bras Cubas
**[[Petrônio Gontijo]] as young Bras Cubas
*[[Viétia Rocha]] as Vírgilia
*[[Sônia Braga]] as Marcela
*[[Otávio Müller]] as Lobo Neves
*[[Marcos Caruso]] as Quincas Borba
*Stepan Nercessian as Bento Cubas
*Débora Duboc as Dona Eusébia
*[[Walmor Chagas]] as Dr. Villaça
*Nilda Spencer as Dona Plácida
*[[Milena Toscano]] as Eugênia

==Production==
Klotzel started to adapt the novel and search for sponsors in 1996; the production was done in 1998, and it was shot in 1999.<ref name=estadao/> A co-production between Brazil and Portugal,<ref name=terra/> ''Memórias Póstumas'' had a budget of about R$4.5–5 million<ref name=estadao>{{cite web | url=http://www.estadao.com.br/arquivo/arteelazer/2001/not20010801p2331.htm | title="Memórias Póstumas" tem pré-estréia em São Paulo | date=August 1, 2001 | work=[[O Estado de S. Paulo]] | publisher=Grupo Estado | accessdate=April 27, 2014 | language=Portuguese }}</ref><ref name=atarde>{{cite web | url=http://cineinsite.atarde.uol.com.br/materia/materia.php?id_filme=5440&id_materia=337 | title=Cineasta paulista lança versão de "Memórias Póstumas de Brás Cubas" | work=A Tarde | date=August 8, 2001 | publisher=[[Universo Online]] | }}</ref> ($2,006,509–2,229,455). It was shot in about 60 filming locations at eight cities, including [[São Paulo]], [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Parati]], [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]] and [[Coimbra]], which lasted twelve weeks.<ref name=atarde/><ref name=lumiere>{{cite web | url=http://www.lumiere.net.nz/reader/item/952 | title=Latin American Film Festival: Posthumous Memoirs | date=April 24, 2007 | work=The Lumière Reader | publisher=Lumière Industries | accessdate=April 27, 2014 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115190703/http://lumiere.net.nz/reader/item/952 | archivedate=January 15, 2015 | df= }}</ref>

==Release and reception==
Its worldwide premiere occurred at the Panorama section of the 2001 [[Berlin International Film Festival]],<ref name=berlin>{{cite web | url=http://www.berlinale.de/external/en/filmarchiv/doku_pdf/20011539.pdf | title=Memórias Póstumas | publisher=[[Berlin International Film Festival]] | accessdate=April 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://cinemateca.gov.br/cgi-bin/wxis.exe/iah/?IsisScript=iah/iah.xis&base=FILMOGRAFIA&lang=p&nextAction=lnk&exprSearch=ID=022299&format=detailed.pft#1 | title=Memórias Póstumas: Brás Cubas | publisher=Cinemateca Brasileira | accessdate=April 27, 2014 | language=Portuguese}}</ref> and it was well received by the public.<ref name=terra>{{cite web | url=http://www.terra.com.br/cinema/gramado2001/2001/08/09/002.htm | title=''Memórias Póstumas'' é a atração de hoje | date=August 9, 2001 | publisher=[[Terra Networks]] | accessdate=April 27, 2014 | language=Portuguese}}</ref> ''Memórias Póstumas'' competed at the 18th [[International Film Festival of Kerala]],<ref name=kerala>{{cite web | url=http://www.iffk.in/index.php?page=archives_02 | title=IFFK Archives: 2002 | publisher=[[International Film Festival of Kerala]] | accessdate=April 27, 2014}}</ref> and won five awards at the 29th [[Festival de Gramado]]: Best Critic's Choice Film, Best Jury's Choice Film, Best Director, Best Screenplay and Best Supporting Actress for Braga.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/fsp/ilustrad/fq1308200117.htm | title='Memórias Póstumas' leva 5 troféus em Gramado | date=August 13, 2001 | author=Arantes, Silvana | work=[[Folha de S. Paulo]] | publisher=Grupo Folha | accessdate=April 27, 2014 | language=Portuguese}}</ref> Its release in Brazil was on August 17, 2001, and it grossed R$855,484 ($381,452) with an attendance of 186,380 people in the 57 theatres in which it was released.<ref name=ancine/> 

It was also well received by English-language critics. Kate Blackhurst from ''The Lumière Reader'' said "I can see why it won several international film awards, and its excellence lies in the fact that it is almost impossible to explain."<ref name=lumiere/> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''{{'}}s Eddie Cockrell "Andre Klotzel revisits distinctive brand of local telenovela melodrama he knows best, with spoofy results that will put pic in demand at fests. Theatrical may be a bit iffier, although vid and tube life will be spry."<ref name=variety>{{cite web | url=https://variety.com/2001/film/reviews/posthumous-memories-1200467280/ | title=Review: ‘Posthumous Memories’ | author=Cockrell, Eddie | date=March 16, 2001 | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] | accessdate=April 27, 2014}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Elvis Mitchell]] stated it has a "hilarious poise", adding that the film "is playful and formal".<ref name=nytimes>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/08/09/movies/critic-s-notebook-a-festival-of-latin-films-that-go-many-different-places.html| title=Critic's Notebook; A Festival of Latin Films That Go Many Different Places | author=[[Elvis Mitchell|Mitchell, Elvis]] | work=[[The New York Times]] | publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] | accessdate=April 27, 2014}}</ref>

